In general, the different layers in the OLED, if present, have the following thicknesses:
anode layer: 50 to 500 nm, preferably 100 to 200 nm;
hole-injection layer (optional): 1 to 50 nm, preferably 5 to 10 nm;
hole-transporting layer (optional): 5 to 100 nm, preferably 10 to 80 nm;
electron-blocking layer (optional): 1 to 50 nm, preferably 5 to 10 nm;
exciton-blocking layer (optional): 1 to 50 nm, preferably 5 to 10 nm;
light-emitting layer: 1 to 100 nm, preferably 5 to 60 nm;
hole-blocking layer (optional): 1 to 50 nm, preferably 5 to 10 nm;
electron-transporting layer (optional): 5 to 100 nm, preferably 20 to 60 nm;
electron-injection layer (optional): 1 to 20 nm, preferably 1 to 5 nm;
cathode layer: 20 to 1000 nm, preferably 30 to 500 nm.
